          Introduction
          Introduction
          Introduction
          Introduction
ç          ____________
 
ç          The  VMARC  program  is a data compaction and file archiving
ç          utility for VM/CMS.  It grew from a project to develop a re-
ç          placement for the CARD utility that would have similar  file
ç          packaging  abilities  coupled with superior data compaction.
ç          VMARC has three basic functions: PACK, UNPACK, and LIST.
 
ç          The PACK function reads ordinary CMS files and produces  the
ç          equivalent  file in a compacted form.  The compacted version
ç          of the file is usually significantly smaller than  the  ori-
ç          ginal,  and  therefore would occupy less disk space or would
ç          require less time to transmit through a network.  VMARC  al-
ç          lows  more than one compacted file to be written to the same
          output file.  The latter is called an archive; the  individ-
ç                                                _______
          ual compacted files are members of the archive.
ç                                  _______
 
ç          Although  compacted files may make economical use of storage
ç          space or network bandwidth, they are not directly usable  by
ç          applications.    The UNPACK function of VMARC reads archives
ç          created by PACK and regenerates the original files from  the
ç          archive members.
 
ç          The LIST function scans archives created by PACK and reports
ç          the names of each of the members.
 
ç          Two  data  compaction  methods  are available, both of which
ç          give very good performance for most  applications.    Method
ç          LZW  is  a  variant of the well-known Lempel-Ziv-Welch algo-
ç          rithm, while S2 is a string-pair algorithm.   The S2  method
ç          tends  to  produce  a  smaller result, but at the expense of
ç          about twice the execution time during compaction.  (However,
ç          there is no performance penalty when  uncompacting  S2  mem-
ç          bers;  the  speed  of  the two methods are comparable.)  The
ç          following compaction results are typical for the LZW and  S2
ç          methods.
 
                                       | Raw size|Method LZWMethod S2
ç                                                           |
ç                     CMS file          | (bytes) | (bytes) | (bytes)
              ◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊
ç                                       |         |         |
ç                   DMSSP MACLIB        |2,760,000|  626,960|  510,240
ç                   SMART MODULE        |1,686,748|   53,440|   46,160
ç                  PLICOMP TXTLIB       |2,224,960|1,190,080|1,114,800
 
ç          Since  there  are cases when neither of the two methods will
ç          produce a result smaller than the original, VMARC  offers  a
ç          compaction  option of STORE.  No compaction is actually done
ç          in this case; the original file data is written as-is to the
ç          output file with only some structural information added.
 
ç          In the initial phases of development of VMARC,  the  utility
ç          was  targeted  as  a replacement for the CARD program.  CARD
ç          has become quite popular within Bitnet because of its  abil-
 
ç          VMARC                                                      4
ª 
                               VMARC Version 1.2
                               VMARC Version 1.2
                               VMARC Version 1.2
ç                               VMARC Version 1.2
 
ç          ity  to build archives for distribution through an RSCS net-
ç          work.    VMARC  as  has  the  same   flavor   of   archiving
ç          capabilities  coupled  with data compaction methods superior
ç          to  the  limited  compaction offered by CARD.  The following
ç          comparison was derived from the MAILER V2.04 distribution.
 
                                       |CARD DUMP|Method LZWMethod S2
ç                                                           |
ç                     CMS file          |(records)|(records)|(records)
              ◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊◊
ç                                       |         |         |
ç                  VMM204 package       |    6,777|    3,875|    3,390
ç                  V2-MNT package       |    4,752|    3,075|    2,867
