ç          The  exact  actions of the PACK function vary depending upon
ç          how the file identifier parameters are specified, and  which
ç          options  are requested.  A few examples may help clarify its
ç          behavior.
 
          Example #1. The Fortran source  code  for  some  application
          Example #1.
          Example #1.
ç          Example #1.
ç          needs  to  be sent to user GEORGE on a system with RSCS node
ç          name NETNODE2.
 
ç            SPOOL PUNCH RSCS
ç            TAG DEVICE PUNCH NETNODE2 GEORGE
ç            VMARC PACK * FORTRAN A ( PUNCH
 
          Example #2. All FORTRAN source is to be placed into individ-
          Example #2.
          Example #2.
ç          Example #2.
ç          ual archives.  These archives are to serve as on-line  back-
ç          ups of the original.
 
ç            VMARC PACK  * FORTRAN A  = VMARC A
 
          Example  #3.  All modules and EXEC files from the B-disk are
          Example  #3.
          Example  #3.
ç          Example  #3.
ç          to be placed into a single archive.  This archive may  be  a
ç          distribution package from some product.
 
ç            VMARC PACK  * MODULE B  PACKAGE VMARC A  (REPLACE
ç            VMARC PACK  * EXEC   B  PACKAGE VMARC A  (APPEND
 
          Example  #4. Development on some project has been completed,
          Example  #4.
          Example  #4.
ç          Example  #4.
ç          so all assembler source files on the C-disk are  to  be  re-
ç          placed  by  their individual archives.  This will reduce the
ç          amount of disk space used by the source, but keep it on-line
ç          in a form where the original  source  can  be  recovered  if
ç          needed.
 
ç            VMARC PACK  * ASSEMBLE C  = = = (REPLACE
 
          Example #5. All files on the D-disk are backed-up to tape.
          Example #5.
          Example #5.
ç          Example #5.
 
ç            VMARC PACK  * * D  (TAP1 BLOCK 8196
ç            TAPE WTM 2
