ç          Æ   No function specified.
 
ç              No  function was specified on the VMARC command line, or
ç              the function specified was not recognized as valid.  The
ç              first parameter on the command line must  be  PACK,  UN-
ç              PACK, or LIST.  Correct the command line, then retry the
ç              command.
 
ç          Æ   Output file specification invalid.
 
ç              The  file name, type or mode entered for the output file
ç              contains invalid characters.   Verify  that  the  output
ç              file  name  or  pattern is entered correctly.  Retry the
ç              command.
 
ç          Æ   Output disk full.
 
ç              The disk where the output file is being written is full.
ç              Free up space for the output file  by  erasing  unneeded
ç              files or by selecting a different disk for output.
 
ç          Æ   Output disk is read/only.
 
ç              The output file cannot be written because the disk spec-
ç              ified  for  output  is read only.   Either re-access the
ç              disk as writable, or select a different disk for output.
 
ç          Æ   Output file already exists.
 
ç              The output file specified already exists,  and  the  RE-
ç              PLACE  option was not specified. Select a different name
ç        |     for the output file, or include the REPLACE ASKREPLA, or
ç        |     NEWREPLA option on the command line if the existing file
ç              may be overwritten.
 
ç          Æ   Output file has variable record format.
 
ç              VMARC was asked to append to an  existing  archive,  but
ç              the  output  file  has variable length records.  All ar-
ç              chives created  by  VMARC  have  fixed  length  records.
ç              Specify a different output file, then retry the command.
 
ç          Æ   Output file specification invalid.
 
ç              The  file name, type or mode entered for the output file
ç              contains invalid characters.   Verify  that  the  output
ç              file  name  or  pattern is entered correctly.  Retry the
ç              command.
 
